chools decoupled themselves from China and survived. A Malay-dominated government of independent Peninsular Malaysia allowed Chinese primary schools to continue, but finally changed many Chinese secondary schools into National Type Secondary Schools using Malay as the main medium of instruction. Those that remained independent, along with Chinese colleges, continued without government assistance. The Chinese community today continues to safeguard its educational institutions to ensure they survive.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aChinesexEducationzMalaysiaxHistory. 0aChinese--Education--Malaysia--History. 0aEducation and statezMalaysiaxHistory. 0aEducation and state--Malaysia--History. 0aEducationzMalaysiaxHistory. 0aEducation--Malaysia--History. 0aSchools, ChinesexGovernment policyzMalaysia. 0aSchools, ChinesezMalaysiaxHistory. 0aSchools, Chinese--Government policy--Malaysia. 0aSchools, Chinese--Malaysia--History. 7aEDUCATION / Organizations & Institutions.2bisacsh1 aHui, Lee Ting, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311102470708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066300608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z97831106066830 cprintz978981427921540uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981427922240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789814279222423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789814279222/original  a978-3-11-060668-3  ISEAS eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook